<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="255" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1534,1885]" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">
In addition to the new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1809" box="[526,629,1535,1560]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Leptopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Malpighiales" pageId="9" pageNumber="255" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[526,629,1535,1560]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">Leptopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described above, the small water strider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kolenati" authorityYear="1857" box="[1091,1224,1534,1560]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[1091,1224,1534,1560]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">Velia affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was also collected from two of the caves investigated. The species was previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1054,1099,1571,1597]" name="Iran" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">Iran</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ghahari, H. &amp; Moulet, P. &amp; Ostovan, H. &amp; Linnavuori, R. E." box="[1144,1387,1570,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="255" pagination="301 - 342" refId="ref6592" refString="Ghahari, H., Moulet, P., Ostovan, H. &amp; Linnavuori, R. E. (2013) An annotated catalog of the Iranian Dipsocoromorpha, Enicocephalomorpha, Gerromorpha, Leptopodomorpha and Nepomorpha (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Zootaxa, 3641 (4), 301 - 342. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3641.4.1" type="journal article" year="2013">
Ghahari 
<emphasis box="[1243,1301,1570,1596]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
, but from surface waters. During the course of the current investigations, five females and one male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kolenati" authorityYear="1857" box="[1243,1375,1606,1632]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[1243,1375,1606,1632]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">Velia affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected in the twilight and lighted zones of Dasht-e Shir 2 Cave and Cheshmeh Ta’laou Cave (
<figureCitation box="[1218,1351,1642,1668]" captionStart="FIGURES 11, 12" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1045,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,181,1020]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 11, 12. Interior views of Chesmeh Ta’alou Cave, Iran, collection locality for Velia affinis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3758321" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3758321/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
), but in different 
<typeStatus box="[254,313,1679,1705]" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">types</typeStatus>
of habitat. In the Dasht-e Shir cave there is a water feature in the lighted zone of cave system which might be fed by underground waters, with the water level here changing in response to variations in seasonal precipitation. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kolenati" authorityYear="1857" box="[432,530,1750,1776]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[432,530,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">V. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected from the twilight zone close to the lighted zone. By contrast, the Chesmeh Ta’alou Cave is a channel with a low ceiling (
<figureCitation box="[763,895,1786,1812]" captionStart="FIGURES 11, 12" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1045,1070]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,181,1020]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 11, 12. Interior views of Chesmeh Ta’alou Cave, Iran, collection locality for Velia affinis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3758321" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3758321/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
), located down in a valley with muddy substrate, and is provided with water from the entrance to the twilight zone. The amount of annual precipitation affects the water level here as well. The specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kolenati" authorityYear="1857" box="[633,731,1858,1884]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Velia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[633,731,1858,1884]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="255">V. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were again collected from the twilight zone of the cave.
</paragraph>
